R ELEVEN Marwanid Inscriptions -- tCHAPTER TWELVE The Rise of New Epigraphic Languages in the Medieval Islamic East: The Interplay of Persian, Turkish and Arabic on Inscriptions -- tCHAPTER THIRTEEN Inscriptions from the Golden Horde Period and the Crimean Khanate in Crimea: A Body of Hitherto Neglected Material within the Study of the Inscriptions of Islamic Lands -- tPART IV INSCRIBED OBJECTS -- tCHAPTER FOURTEEN The Epigraphic Samarra Horizon: Blue-on-White Ceramics -- tCHAPTER FIFTEEN Art with Poetry: Inscriptions on Mamluk Metalwork -- tCHAPTER SIXTEEN ‘The Calligrapher is An Ape!’ Arabic Epigrams on Pen Boxes (Sixth/ Twelfth–Ninth/Fifteenth Centuries) -- tCHAPTER SEVENTEEN Between the Artist and the Patron: Painted Inscriptions of the Khamsa of Shah Ṭahmāsb -- tPART V EPIGRAPHIC STYLE AND FUNCTION -- tCHAPTER EIGHTEEN The Influence of Aesthetics on Orthographic Decisions in the Early Islamic Graffiti of Wadi al-Khirqa, Northern Hijaz -- tCHAPTER NINETEEN The Here and the Hereafter: Rounded and Angular Inscriptions in Medieval Syria, Anatolia and the Jazira -- tCHAPTER TWENTY Luted Letters: The Relief Inscriptions on Kashan Lustre Mihrabs -- tCHAPTER TWENTY-ONE Carved Letters, Designs and Ornaments: Ilkhanid Stuccos and the ‘Signatures’ of their Craftsmen -- tCHAPTER TWENTY-TWO The Qutb Minar: Epigraphic Notes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aShowcases the best recent research on epigraphy across the medieval Islamic worldExplores Islamic epigraphy from a wide range of perspectives and geographical areas, from the Maghreb to India and Central Asia and beyondCovers the period from the rise of Islam to the 15th centuryDetails 20 case studies of inscriptions found on a wide range of objects from coins, pen cases, textiles, tiles, pottery and wall paintings to public buildings, monuments, tombs, minarets, monasteries and madrasasBeautifully illustrated with 200 colour photographs of inscriptions on buildings and objectsIncludes contributions from some of the leading experts in the field including Jonathan Bloom, Robert Hillenbrand, Sheila Blair, Doris Behrens-Abouseif and Carole HillenbrandThis volume offers an overview of the state of the field, and shows the importance of Islamic inscriptions for disciplines such as art history, history and literature. The chapters range from surveys to detailed exploration of individual topics, providing an insight to some of the most recent cutting-edge work on Islamic inscriptions. It focuses on the period from the rise of Islam to the fifteenth century, ranging across the Islamic world from the Maghreb to India and Central Asia, and inscriptions in Arabic, Persian and Turkish.The five sections of the book draw together some of the principal themes: ‘Royal Power’ investigates the role of sultanic patronage in epigraphy, and the use of inscriptions for projecting royal power. ‘Piety’ examines the relationship between epigraphy and religious practice. ‘Epigraphic Style and Function’ explores the relationship between the use of specific epigraphic styles and scripts and the function of a monument. ‘Inscribed Objects’ moves from monumental inscriptions to those on objects such as ceramics and pen-cases. The final section considers the interplay between inscriptions and historical sources as well as the utility of inscriptions as historical sources.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivilization, MedievalvSources. 0aIslamic civilizationvSources. 0aIslamic inscriptionsxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aVisual communicationxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aIslamic Studies. 70(DE-588)4027107-90(DE-627)10628598X0(DE-576)208969276aInschrift2gnd 70(DE-588)4129108-60(DE-627)1045354740(DE-576)209607793aMittelalter2gnd 7aARCHITECTURE / Decoration & Ornament.2b